title: For Sale:  12gauge Mossberg 500AB  w/scope 6-shot pump  30" barrel
postcontent:
Mossberg 500AB 12 gauge 6+1 pump, beautiful gun, walnut, nice shotgun..with a picatinny rail mounted Red Dot scope. The 500AB is the 500A Mossberg shotgun with some improvements...specifically a Walnut stock VS the various hardwood stocks found on the regular 500A model. My 500AB also has some etchings in the receiver metal ,as seen in 1 photo, that the 500A does not have ...and it has a 30" barrel. (Every part on this 500AB is interchangeable with the regular 500A)
This is a fixed full choke 30" barreled shotgun. Thirty inches is a long range shotgun. Perfect for Deer /Water Fowl...and well, anything. You get the 100 yard reach of a rifle, with the spread pattern of a shotgun. Full choke means it keeps it's shot pattern tight over a long distance, so you get killing/stopping power at rifle like distances. It shoots bird and buck shot and rifled slugs. It is chambered for 2&3/4" and 3.00" shells. I'll include a box of shells with it...I won't need them if I sell the shotgun. It functions flawlessly and it looks great. The walnut is beautiful. The bore is beautiful inside...slick as a whistle. It also has a metal safety switch, not a plastic one like the newer Mossbergs. It has a Tasco Red Dot scope, a good one, that enables quick sholdering and accurate firing of shotgun. For those folks who don't know what a Red Dot scope is: You turn the switch on and the red dot is displayed in the scope lens...when you look thru the scope, wherever the dot is - that's where the bullet goes. If you move your head, the red dot stays on the target your pointing at and you can still see the dot as you move your head around. It makes for very quick and accurate shooting. I love this shotgun, and the new owner will too. I need money, I have to sell it. Three hundred is as low as I'll go. A box of shells #6 shot- I think they are, go with it. Thanks.

title: For Sale:  1960s Inox Stilleto Switchblade
postcontent:
I wasn't sure what to think of this when I found it. I've owned butterfly knives and one switchblade in the past and I obviously knew what a switchblade should be, but this outdid my expectations. It functions beaufully and looks great. On doing a google search, I found out that these are pretty sought out 1950s to 60s knives that can range as high as $400. The handle is some sort of horn I think, and other than that I know nothing about it beside the fact its really really sharp, stainless steel and patented. 
The blade is 3.5 inches and the knife has an overall length of 8 inches. It says "Inox" on one side of the blade and "Patent 96847" on the other. The knife has a bayonet blade (this makes it somewhat easier to pull out of a soft target), a standard slide-safety and the handle is  animal horn stained in a deep brown/black. No rust, no heavy scratches, nicks or scrapes. The only thing that keeps this weapon out of the "mint" category is the fact that it's obvious the blade has seen more than her share of a sharpening stone. That is probably this knife was used as it was intended: either as an easy one-handed access tool for craftsmen and campers or as an intimidating weapon  This knife came in a genuine leather belt-loop Buck pouch (in which it fits perfectly) and so I see no reasons it shouldn't come with it. Email me to see more pictures.

I will accept only TWO types of ammo in trade, .308 Winchester or 9x19 Luger. But if you want to do that, keep in mind that I want $110 dollars worth of it.
